        "content": "<p>It may be possible that we may need to compose system of different <em>types</em>, for example composing a Petri net with a monoid labeled graph, composing a differential equation based dynamical system with a Boolean dynamical system, etc. Below,  I briefly describng a scenario where such composition can be natural.</p>\n<p>Let us assume we are studying  interaction among  large number of biochemical entities.   It may happen that due to the availability-unavaibility  of data,  some of the interactions are possible to be modeled as reaction networks with rates and some are possible to be modeled only as signed/monoid labeled  graphs. Similarly, at the level of dynamics, we may need to model the dynamics of some interactions using logic and some using O.D.E. Thus, the  whole system can be seen as a hybrid system : a mix of Petri nets and signed graphs, and a mix of Boolean networks and O.D.E's. </p>\n<p>In ACT frameworks, I think usually we  comopose systems of <em>similar nature</em> i.e</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Petri nets with rates with Petri nets with rates</li>\n<li>Petri nets with Petri nets</li>\n<li>Signed graphs with signed graphs</li>\n<li>O.D.E with O.D.E</li>\n<li>.</li>\n<li>. so on</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>My question is the following:</strong><br>\nAre there existing  ACT-based frameworks which allow composing networks of different types? In that case, it seems like we need to compose a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> of a categoy <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> with a morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> of category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>.  More broadly, how to compose models of different types using ACT ?</p>",
        "id": 570349748,
        "sender_full_name": "Adittya Chaudhuri",
        "timestamp": 1769527459
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>While there seems to be an obvious answer, I'm not sure it's what you're looking for. In any case:</p>\n<p>Let's say that our \"types of system\" are each some sort of category, and that our individual systems of some type are morphisms in that category. For example, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> a morphism of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> a morphism of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span></span></span></span>. One way to reason about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> together is to embed them into some common domain <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> via functors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A : \\mathbb{A} \\to \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B : \\mathbb{B} \\to \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 570355721,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1769528798
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course, for this to work you need a suitable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span>, being a \"type of system\" that is flexible enough to accommodate both <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span></span></span></span>. In a perfect world you would also have that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> have nice properties. For example, it would be very nice if they were faithful.</p>",
        "id": 570356180,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1769528904
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, and there is a particularly common case where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}=\\mathbb{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}=\\mathbb{B}.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 570379330,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1769534533
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"609515\">@Kevin Carlson</span>   <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"690871\">@Chad Nester</span> !! I got the point. Then, by a <em>nice</em> functorial relationship between the corresponding categories  of two different systems (more generally,  with respect to another common category where the corresponding categories can be embedded) we can  build a composable framework for the hybrid system.</p>",
        "id": 570382354,
        "sender_full_name": "Adittya Chaudhuri",
        "timestamp": 1769535407
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But, what if in reality we can not find suitable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\colon \\mathbb{A} \\to \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span>  and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B \\colon \\mathbb{B} \\to \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span>?</p>\n<p>For example, a common hybrid system that is used in the modelling of biological networks is the hybrid of Boolean model and O.D.E based model. In that case, I am not sure how to find  suitable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\colon \\mathbb{A} \\to \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span>  and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B \\colon \\mathbb{B} \\to \\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 570385748,
        "sender_full_name": "Adittya Chaudhuri",
        "timestamp": 1769536355
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hybrid dynamical systems can often already be placed in their own category in a perfectly natural way, depending on the formalism, which you haven't quite specified. The simplest case is of simply allowing differential equations with some discontinuities, as in the bouncing ball system. There is no big problem to building <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span> as the category of all such differential equation systems. But you may mean something quite different. There's no general answer to constructing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> that doesn't look at the details of a given case without degrading into triviality.</p>",
        "id": 570386794,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1769536637
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!! I got your point.</p>",
        "id": 570399038,
        "sender_full_name": "Adittya Chaudhuri",
        "timestamp": 1769539972
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In my talks these days I always advertise composing systems of different types by mapping two (double) categories to a common (double) category, as Chad suggests.   Following <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275965\">@Evan Patterson</span>, I call this 'interoperability'.    My favorite example is composing Petri nets with rates and stock-flow diagrams by mapping them both to dynamical systems:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/6sK1wu4E2b0rPyWK-SnxR8cv/AIM_modeling_with_categories.pdf\">Modeling with applied category theory</a> (page 30 of 31).</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 570429029,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1769550400
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Though this should be rather easy in the AlgebraicJulia framework, I don't know of anyone actually doing it there yet!</p>",
        "id": 570429106,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1769550433
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/How.20to.20compose.20systems.20of.20different.20.60types'.20using.20ACT.20.3F/near/570429029\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In my talks these days I always advertise composing systems of different types by mapping two (double) categories to a common (double) category, as Chad suggests.   Following <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275965\">Evan Patterson</span>, I call this 'interoperability'.    My favorite example is composing Petri nets with rates and stock-flow diagrams by mapping them both to dynamical systems:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/6sK1wu4E2b0rPyWK-SnxR8cv/AIM_modeling_with_categories.pdf\">Modeling with applied category theory</a> (page 30 of 31).</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thanks a lot. This is exactly what I was asking.  I was not aware of this natural idea of interoperability in ACT before.</p>",
        "id": 570474596,
        "sender_full_name": "Adittya Chaudhuri",
        "timestamp": 1769579838
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wish people would start actually <em>doing</em> it!</p>",
        "id": 570480192,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1769582984
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Has much been done on theory or operad mappings? In <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2105.12282\">Operadic Modeling of Dynamical Systems: Mathematics and Computation</a>, the authors consider three systems theories:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/g9evXr1Qwyb_rp_SBUDhTMDr/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/g9evXr1Qwyb_rp_SBUDhTMDr/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"634x289\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/g9evXr1Qwyb_rp_SBUDhTMDr/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>They discuss a functor from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mi>W</mi><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Th(DWD)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Th(CPG)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">CPG</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, engendering an adjoint triple between  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mi>W</mi><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[Th(DWD), Set]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[Th(CPG), Set]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">CPG</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>. There's a corresponding operad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">CPG</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">CPG</span></span></span></span> which is a suboperad of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi><mi>W</mi><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">DWD</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>.  </p>\n<p>Has anything been done at a general level about the collection of such theories/operads? When are there colimits of such things, etc.?</p>",
        "id": 570511040,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1769593639
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Could we see <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276589\">@Sophie Libkind</span>'s amalgamation of the directed and undirected settings in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2007.14442\">An Algebra of Resource Sharing Machines</a> in terms of a colimit?</p>",
        "id": 570512490,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1769594059
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Obviously people have studied things like the category of operads (for some flavour) and can prove things like:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>the category <em>Operad</em> is small complete and small cocomplete, (Weiss, <a href=\"https://dspace.library.uu.nl/bitstream/handle/1874/22859/c1.pdf\">Operads</a>)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>and also a symmetric closed monoidal category .</p>\n<p>But I'm wondering more about in the ACT context of systems.</p>",
        "id": 570516705,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1769595254
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A related question: I wonder how much is known about sorts of structured category for which the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/amalgamation+property\">amalgamation property</a> holds.</p>",
        "id": 570569516,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1769609888
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess the higher-level question of when we can \"amalgamate\" different sorts of structure on a category is also relevant here. For example, if our <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span></span></span></span> are each different sorts of structured category (say in the sense of KZ-monads), and their structures are \"amalgamable\", and also this amalgamated sort of structure (call it <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>) is such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-structured categories have some sort of amalgamation property, then there should be a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-structured category into which both <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">B</span></span></span></span> embed.</p>",
        "id": 570571528,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1769610296
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So you could probably study this kind of thing with \"system interoperability\" as your motivation.</p>",
        "id": 570572255,
        "sender_full_name": "Chad Nester",
        "timestamp": 1769610441
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"690871\">Chad Nester</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/How.20to.20compose.20systems.20of.20different.20.60types'.20using.20ACT.20.3F/near/570569516\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A related question: I wonder how much is known about sorts of structured category for which the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/amalgamation+property\">amalgamation property</a> holds.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>For mathematical structures that form 1-categories, the structure possesses the amalgamation property precisely when the 1-category of those structures has all pushouts (or at minimum all pushouts of monos) and those pushouts preserve monos. This is easy to see: if you have objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A, B, C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> embeds into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> via having monos into them, all you need to do is just take the pushout. This \"glues together\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> along <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, and by our assumption of mono preservation, the projections of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> into the pushout are monos. The pushout square is automatically commutative, and thus amalgamation is satisfied. Common cases of categories where this is true are adhesive categories.</p>\n<p>So you'd just need to define a 2-categorical version of this property, and then check if your target 2-category of structured 1-categories satisfies it.</p>",
        "id": 570651635,
        "sender_full_name": "John Onstead",
        "timestamp": 1769631244
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Saying \"precisely when\" is wrong.  For example, the finite linear orders (forming the augmented simplex category) have amalgamation, but they don't have pushouts.</p>",
        "id": 570820869,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1769699286
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Agreed: pushouts  provide a universal choice of amalgamation when they exist, but they needn't!</p>",
        "id": 570858328,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1769708289
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Fields are another classic example of this problem. You study the \"compositum\" of two subfields of a common extension in Galois theory, but this compositum can vary based on the common extension, and so is not a pushout.</p>",
        "id": 570858733,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1769708399
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You're right, my apologies, I only showed the connection in one direction. I probably should have said \"when\" instead of \"precisely when\". From a practical perspective, proving that pushouts exist and preserve monos for a category might in many cases be the simplest way to show the amalgamation property holds (since pushouts are universal constructions we can do good computations with), but if it doesn't work then whether amalgamation is satisfied remains inconclusive.</p>",
        "id": 570905284,
        "sender_full_name": "John Onstead",
        "timestamp": 1769724784
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not to get too far off the original topic, but I did think of another way to do a category-theoretic interpretation of amalgamation I think works better. Define <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Sub}^{op}(A)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sub</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7487em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> to be the subobject poset of monos <em>out of</em> the object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, which is reverse to how things are normally done with the usual subobject poset of monos <em>into</em> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> (and not to be confused with the opposite of the usual subobject poset!). Then amalgamation appears to be precisely the property that for every <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> in the category, this poset is directed (every pair of subobjects out of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> share an upper bound, which would be an amalgamation). That said while this is a more precise category theoretic interpretation, it's probably much harder to computationally/practically show than the pushout property.</p>",
        "id": 570905296,
        "sender_full_name": "John Onstead",
        "timestamp": 1769724789
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, that's a more refined formulation. Less convenient but quite important, as preservation of monos by pushout is an exceptionally special property.</p>",
        "id": 570906429,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1769725153
    }
]